{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Shair* (\"The Poet\"), from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the Urdu word **shaair** (شاعر, poet) is elevated beyond mere artistry to embody the perceptive conscience and empathetic voice of the nation (**qaum**). Iqbal deploys an organic body metaphor for the nation: its people are limbs, hands and feet pursue industry and commerce, and government adorns its face.[^1] The **shaair**, by contrast, is the nation's \"seeing eye\" (**deeda-e-beena-e-qaum**) and \"colorful voice\" (**rangeen nawa**), acutely sensitive to collective suffering—like an eye that weeps whenever any limb aches.[^2] This thematic weight underscores the poet's prophetic role in awakening national self-awareness, voicing pain, and illuminating vision amid colonial fragmentation.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 39 (\"Shair\"), [paragraphs p-4562af to p-b2f13c](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/39-shair/translation/#p-4562af).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 39 (\"Shair\"), [paragraph p-6afdc8](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/39-shair/translation/#p-6afdc8).",
